     An important figure of merit in quantum memories is the fidelity of the state being read out compared to that which was stored. Ideally, the output pulse should be identical in amplitude and phase to the input pulse. In reality, distortions and loss induced by storage in the PADL and thermal noise reduce the fidelity. We will show that the latter is negligible in our system and first focus on distortion and loss. Given two pulses that are characterized by temporal mode operators








